  310: {
    beginner: `Egocentric Bias = The tendency to rely too heavily on one's own perspective and to underestimate the viewpoints of others.`,
    detail: `Egocentric Bias

Description:
The tendency to rely too heavily on one's own perspective and to underestimate the viewpoints of others.
Thinking you are the main character of the universe.

Example (question)
« Thinking my opinion is the most important. »
This is the exact kind of move the question is testing.

Example (everyday)
The argument overestimates the degree to which one's own perspective, actions, or feelings are the center of events or noticed by others.
The same logic shows up even when the surface story changes.

How it works
The argument uses the surface clue as if it were enough to settle the claim.

So:
- Most people are thinking about themselves, not about you.
- We overestimate our contribution to group efforts.
- It makes us think our personal experience is the universal rule.

Key concept inside it
Spotlight Effect:
The phenomenon where people tend to believe they are being noticed more than they really are.

Why it matters
Explains why:
- Most people are thinking about themselves, not about you.
- We overestimate our contribution to group efforts.
- It makes us think our personal experience is the universal rule.

The uncomfortable implication
You will suffer immense anxiety worrying about judgments that nobody is actually making.

One-line version
Egocentric Bias = The tendency to rely too heavily on one's own perspective and to underestimate the viewpoints of others.`,
  },
