  313: {
    beginner: `False Consensus Effect = The tendency for people to overestimate the degree to which others agree with them.`,
    detail: `False Consensus Effect

Description:
The tendency for people to overestimate the degree to which others agree with them.
Assuming everyone agrees with you.

Example (question)
« Assuming everyone agrees with my unpopular view. »
This is the exact kind of move the question is testing.

Example (everyday)
The argument assumes that one's own opinions, beliefs, and values are normal and shared by the majority of people.
The same logic shows up even when the surface story changes.

How it works
The argument uses the surface clue as if it were enough to settle the claim.

So:
- We surround ourselves with people who think like us.
- It makes opposing views seem not just wrong, but bizarre or fringe.
- It destroys the ability to understand different perspectives.

Key concept inside it
Echo Chamber:
An environment where a person only encounters information or opinions that reflect and reinforce their own.

Why it matters
Explains why:
- We surround ourselves with people who think like us.
- It makes opposing views seem not just wrong, but bizarre or fringe.
- It destroys the ability to understand different perspectives.

The uncomfortable implication
You will be constantly shocked by reality because you assume your bubble is the whole world.

One-line version
False Consensus Effect = The tendency for people to overestimate the degree to which others agree with them.`,
  },
