  316: {
    beginner: `Focusing Illusion = The tendency to place too much importance on one aspect of an event.`,
    detail: `Focusing Illusion

Description:
The tendency to place too much importance on one aspect of an event.
Nothing is as important as what you are thinking about right now.

Example (question)
« Thinking money is the most important thing in life. »
This is the exact kind of move the question is testing.

Example (everyday)
The argument drastically overestimates the importance of one specific factor while ignoring all other context.
The same logic shows up even when the surface story changes.

How it works
The argument uses the surface clue as if it were enough to settle the claim.

So:
- If you focus entirely on money, you think money is the only thing that causes happiness.
- It creates tunnel vision in decision making.
- It exaggerates the impact of whatever is currently grabbing your attention.

Key concept inside it
Anchoring:
The human tendency to rely too heavily on the first piece of information offered or focused upon.

Why it matters
Explains why:
- If you focus entirely on money, you think money is the only thing that causes happiness.
- It creates tunnel vision in decision making.
- It exaggerates the impact of whatever is currently grabbing your attention.

The uncomfortable implication
You will make terrible life choices if you let one single factor blind you to the big picture.

One-line version
Focusing Illusion = The tendency to place too much importance on one aspect of an event.`,
  },
