  319: {
    beginner: `Frequency Illusion = The illusion in which a word, name, or thing that has recently come to one's attention suddenly seems to appear with improbable frequency shortly afterwards.`,
    detail: `Frequency Illusion

Description:
The illusion in which a word, name, or thing that has recently come to one's attention suddenly seems to appear with improbable frequency shortly afterwards.
Now that you noticed it, it's everywhere.

Example (question)
« Noticing a new word everywhere after learning it. »
This is the exact kind of move the question is testing.

Example (everyday)
The argument claims a sudden, massive increase in a phenomenon, when in reality the person has just recently learned to notice it.
The same logic shows up even when the surface story changes.

How it works
The argument uses the surface clue as if it were enough to settle the claim.

So:
- Also known as the Baader-Meinhof phenomenon.
- Your brain starts filtering *for* it instead of filtering it *out*.
- It feels like a conspiracy or a sudden trend.

Key concept inside it
Selective Attention:
The process of focusing on a particular object in the environment for a certain period of time while ignoring competing stimuli.

Why it matters
Explains why:
- Also known as the Baader-Meinhof phenomenon.
- Your brain starts filtering *for* it instead of filtering it *out*.
- It feels like a conspiracy or a sudden trend.

The uncomfortable implication
You will mistake your own sudden awareness for a sudden change in the world.

One-line version
Frequency Illusion = The illusion in which a word, name, or thing that has recently come to one's attention suddenly seems to appear with improbable frequency shortly afterwards.`,
  },
