  334: {
    beginner: `Hindsight Bias = The tendency to see past events as being predictable at the time those events happened.`,
    detail: `Hindsight Bias

Description:
The tendency to see past events as being predictable at the time those events happened.
I knew it all along.

Example (question)
« Saying 'I knew it' after an event. »
This is the exact kind of move the question is testing.

Example (everyday)
The argument falsely claims, after an event has occurred, that the event was predictable or obvious all along.
The same logic shows up even when the surface story changes.

How it works
The argument uses the surface clue as if it were enough to settle the claim.

So:
- The past always looks inevitable once it has happened.
- It prevents us from learning because we think we didn't make a mistake.
- It makes us judge past decisions unfairly.

Key concept inside it
Creeping Determinism:
The growing sense, as an event unfolds, that it was bound to happen this way.

Why it matters
Explains why:
- The past always looks inevitable once it has happened.
- It prevents us from learning because we think we didn't make a mistake.
- It makes us judge past decisions unfairly.

The uncomfortable implication
You will never improve your forecasting if you always pretend you saw the surprise coming.

One-line version
Hindsight Bias = The tendency to see past events as being predictable at the time those events happened.`,
  },
