  340: {
    beginner: `Identifiable Victim Effect = The tendency to respond more strongly to identifiable victims than to statistical victims.`,
    detail: `Identifiable Victim Effect

Description:
The tendency to respond more strongly to identifiable victims than to statistical victims.
One face matters more than a million numbers.

Example (question)
« Donating more to help one named child than thousands unnamed. »
This is the exact kind of move the question is testing.

Example (everyday)
The argument relies on the tendency to offer greater aid or sympathy to a specific, identifiable individual than to a large, vaguely defined group with the same need.
The same logic shows up even when the surface story changes.

How it works
The argument uses the surface clue as if it were enough to settle the claim.

So:
- Statistics don't make people cry.
- A single story overrides a spreadsheet of data.
- It misallocates resources to high-profile cases over systemic problems.

Key concept inside it
Compassion Fade:
The phenomenon where people's willingness to help decreases as the number of people in need increases.

Why it matters
Explains why:
- Statistics don't make people cry.
- A single story overrides a spreadsheet of data.
- It misallocates resources to high-profile cases over systemic problems.

The uncomfortable implication
You will give everything to save one person on TV while ignoring thousands dying quietly off-camera.

One-line version
Identifiable Victim Effect = The tendency to respond more strongly to identifiable victims than to statistical victims.`,
  },
