  364: {
    beginner: `Omission Bias = The tendency to judge harmful actions as worse than equally harmful omissions.`,
    detail: `Omission Bias

Description:
The tendency to judge harmful actions as worse than equally harmful omissions.
Doing nothing feels safer than doing something, even when the outcome is the same.

Example (question)
« Thinking lying is worse than not telling the truth. »
This is the exact kind of move the question is testing.

Example (everyday)
The argument judges harmful actions as worse, or less moral, than equally harmful inactions.
The same logic shows up even when the surface story changes.

How it works
The argument uses the surface clue as if it were enough to settle the claim.

So:
- Pulling a lever to kill someone feels worse than watching them die.
- It paralyzes decision-makers in crisis.
- It lets people feel innocent while allowing terrible things to happen.

Key concept inside it
The Trolley Problem:
A thought experiment in ethics about whether to act to save many at the cost of one, or do nothing.

Why it matters
Explains why:
- Pulling a lever to kill someone feels worse than watching them die.
- It paralyzes decision-makers in crisis.
- It lets people feel innocent while allowing terrible things to happen.

The uncomfortable implication
You will let people suffer just so you can keep your own hands clean.

One-line version
Omission Bias = The tendency to judge harmful actions as worse than equally harmful omissions.`,
  },
